Now we have just enough degrees of freedom for three contours, namely, two -space contours  and the contour defined by , whhich can be chosen freely.  It is far from trivial, in general, to find explicitly the target-space contours , although this can be done perturbatively.  One may say that this difficulty is the real difficulty of the Plateau problem, and we have nothing new to say about it.  But from the point of view of QCD dynamics, what is required is not to associate a set of target-space contours to areas, but to integrate over these contours, or areas, in a way consistent with external boundary conditions.  Integrating over the  contours and the  contour will serve just as well, provided that no difficulties are encountered in imposing the boundary conditions.   

